Ecoark: An Overview of How Technology Improves Transparency



Laws govern the way food reaches
consumers through the supply chain. From harvesting to retail, food has a
finite shelf life and each article must meet minimum standards of appearance
and freshness in addition to other parameters. Inefficiencies lead to delays
that result in waste of fresh produce. In the process suppliers may also resort
to practices to minimize their loss and hide facts. This is understandable when
one looks at losses of over $ 160 billion annually due to waste. 
Improving efficiencies and speeding up
processes could help in avoiding this lack of transparency. Food supply chains
rely on traditional methods of moving materials and tracking movements as well
as monitoring condition of produce. A simple switch to the latest food
safety management system is all it takes to ensure food is delivered
fresh and waste is avoided. Technology applied to harvesting helps reduce waste
and improve technology by tracking and prioritizing pallets waiting for the
pre-cooling process prior to shipment. Those in charge can take informed
decisions to match pallets to specific orders when they have information right
at their fingertips. Even during the cooling process the IT solution enables
quality checkers to track product temperatures during the process and notify
workers when it is complete. It does not stop there as transportation is
another roadblock. During this stage fresh produce can remain un-monitored but
not anymore when intelligent tracking systems are in place to ensure critical
monitoring and coordination. Remote visibility powered by technology allows
higher visibility of the product in various stages to help buyers or dealers
accept or reject a product even before it is shipped or before it reaches the
end point. Sellers can use technology to find other buyers and divert the
produce instead of having to discard it. 
Food safety
management systems even take care of visual
inspection of fresh produce to check freshness at all stages, not just at the
last stage. One way this can prove helpful, reduce waste and improve
transparency is that sellers can then route such products according to various
stages of freshness to nearest points of sale or consumption. 
Typically, logistics of fresh produce
movement starts with harvesting and the steps involve cut to cool, pre-cooling,
staging, shipping, transit, wholesale distribution and end point that may be
retail or hotel or food processing. An intelligent, well thought out and
implement software solution factors in all these stages and ensures greater
transparency for all those involved not only to be better informed but to
handle challenges peculiar to each stage. Waste that is currently in billions
of dollars could reduce to a fraction of the amount. Transparency powered by
software leads to greater collaboration and better coordination resulting in
reduced waste. Food is consumed, not discarded. 
The comprehensive solution covers all
aspects in a modular form including pallet level tracking, pre-cooling stage,
pallet routing, in-transit monitoring, freshness quality management and remote
visibility. A smartphone and internet connection is all it takes for everyone
to share and collaborate on best food produce handling techniques in an open,
transparent and meaningful way. 
Resources: http://ecoarkusa.blogspot.in/2016/11/ecoark-overview-of-how-technology.html
 



 



